WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.020
these are my disclosures. So we talk about CAR-T-cells and frontline therapy for myeloma. We're

00:00:09.020 --> 00:00:13.560
really not talking about truly giving CARs to untreated newly diagnosed patients. These studies

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:18.900
are always constructed as consolidation studies because it's not practical to really give a truly

00:00:18.900 --> 00:00:23.940
newly diagnosed patient myeloma, or sorry, truly newly diagnosed patient CAR-T-cell therapy.

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:28.580
So I highlight this one just because it's one of the few that's really been fully published and

00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:33.980
then is also going forward in a larger phase study. So this is GC012F, which is the combo

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:38.720
CD19-BCMA CAR, now with AstraZeneca, with a different name that I can't remember,

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:44.820
ADD0120, I think. So these are patients, they got a couple cycles of VRD,

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:50.180
and then went on to receive CyFlu and CAR-T-cells. And one issue with all these studies you'll see

00:00:50.180 --> 00:00:55.180
is that a few patients during the induction pre-CAR phase peel off the study because maybe

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:58.560
they had very aggressive disease and blew through induction. And so when you see the

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:01.940
results at the end, you also have to interpret that maybe some of the higher risk patients were

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:05.880
selected off. But this is kind of typical of what we see where your patients come in

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:11.060
with a smattering of responses, they get the CAR-T-cell, you see very high rates of MRD negative

00:01:11.060 --> 00:01:16.900
CR afterwards and good progression-free survival, but still not cure. So we still see at least one

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:21.700
patient just in this relatively early follow-up has progressed. You see favorable safety generally,

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:28.540
so primary hematologic AEs, 27% all-grade CRS, all low-grade CRS,

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:33.500
no neurotoxicity. And then with this particular CAR, you don't see long-term persistence,

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:37.420
as I said, 100% MRD negative CR. So that's really impressive.

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:44.940
This is a similar design, although doing the consolidation a bit later. And so this is

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:52.060
cohort D of CAR-T-2. So this was a small group of patients who were in a pilot phase,

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:58.520
evaluated if they had less than CR after induction plus transplant. They got CyFlu, Cilta-cells,

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:02.880
and then resumed blend maintenance. And that's an interesting aspect too. So when we're using

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:07.460
CAR-T-cells as part of first-line therapy where it's not so much one and done like we think about

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:12.640
in the relapse setting, oftentimes these studies are testing resuming maintenance therapy and

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:18.280
recognizing that even CAR-T-cells are not reliably curing patients. So maybe we do have to resume the

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:23.500
maintenance therapy. Again, you see really impressive 94% of the patients upgrade to CR

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:28.500
or stringent CR, most of those being MRD negative. But still, you're still seeing some patients who

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:33.640
relapse even after this intensive course of therapy, transplant, and CAR-T-cells. You're

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:39.680
still seeing CRS, but it's all low-grade. And so probably a safer setting with lower disease burden.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:43.280
But still, even in this low disease burden setting, I mean, these patients are not just

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:47.320
effectively bridged. They're really kind of in a good remission when they come into the CAR-T-cell

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:53.320
therapy. You're still seeing some of these serious neurologic toxicities. Even if they're

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:58.080
low-grade, they're disturbing and they can last for a while and not necessarily completely reversed,

00:02:58.080 --> 00:02:58.480
but no, they're not necessarily completely reversed. But no,

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:04.460
no movement in neurotoxic, no Parkinsonism. Interestingly, one MDS emerging in this study,

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:08.760
and we'll talk later about some of these second malignancy risks.

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:15.420
This is a study that Sergio alluded to earlier that we worked on in the BMT-CTN. This is giving

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:20.080
Ida-cel and kind of a similar setting patients who failed to achieve CR after induction plus

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:26.000
transplant, and then a few months of lenalidomide maintenance. These patients got CyFlu, Ida-cel,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.300
and then resumed len maintenance. We showed that patients could,

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:32.840
safely resumed len maintenance in this setting, and that we saw really nice improvements in

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:38.440
response. And so 79% of patients at 12 months converting to CR, 90% upgrading their response.

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:43.500
And again, Sergio was alluding earlier to where maybe what there might be a sweet spot for Ida-cel.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:47.620
This could be that kind of setting because you really see no neurologic toxicity,

00:03:47.780 --> 00:03:53.160
no secondary malignancies so far, all low-grade CRS. And so if we're, and if we're talking about

00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:58.440
in a frontline setting, first-line therapy using CARs, we really want to have a high safety

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:04.540
bar, and maybe with a less potent, but more safe CAR like Ida-cel, that's a sweet spot for it.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.140
So there's a couple of phase three studies. These were alluded to earlier. So CARTITUDE-5

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:15.240
and CARTITUDE-6 that in a randomized setting where patients are enrolling at very early on,

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:21.720
enrolling to receive CARs in a randomized setting as part of first-line therapy. And so these are

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:27.820
better study designs because you don't worry about the selection away from patients who maybe progress

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:28.420
early on. They'll be able to do it in a better way. And so we're looking at a lot of these studies

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:33.260
that will be included in these analyses. And so we'll see what the results of these show over time.

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:38.060
These studies still don't address the crucial question of sequencing though. And so if we see

00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:44.420
that the CAR-T-cell arm in a frontline study does better, we really have to be confident that we

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:48.740
couldn't get the same long-term outcome by using that CAR-T-cell in second-line therapy. And I

00:04:48.740 --> 00:04:51.980
think that's really important because we have really good data for CAR-T-cells in second and

00:04:51.980 --> 00:04:56.200
third-line therapy. And the question will be, depending on the particular CAR you're talking to,

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:03.960
do we have to take in terms of risk, right? Even if it's a low rate of risk for serious toxicity in

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:07.780
frontline therapy, we have to be confident that we're getting something special by giving it

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:13.080
earlier as opposed to putting off that risk until later. And we already see a little bit of that

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:19.560
emerging in the second and third-line CAR-T-cell data. And so first, as we heard over and over,

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:24.940
DARA-VRD, even with transplant and long-term maintenance therapy, is super safe and super

00:05:24.940 --> 00:05:28.380
effective. And so the safety bar should be very, very high. And so we're looking at a lot of

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:34.960
new treatments in the first-line therapy. And so this is looking even at CAR-T-4, where we're using

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:42.360
CAR-T-cells in one to three prior lines of therapy. You see that maybe even in first relapse,

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:47.880
there might be a little bit of a survival hit you take giving CAR-T-cells due to the risk entailed

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:53.840
in that when you have, as the comparator, very, very effective second-line therapy,

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:58.360
a standard therapy. And I think that question is even more pressing as you move into early

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:03.920
lines of therapy and first-line therapy. And a question of whether you can recoup the benefit

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:07.520
of earlier CARs with later CARs, I think we learned something from CARMA-3. So this was

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:14.140
similar study, Ida-cel in two to four prior lines of therapy, and patients could cross over. And so

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:18.620
you saw a progression-free survival benefit by giving the CARs earlier, but there was no overall

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:22.400
survival benefit, largely because patients who progressed were able to get CAR-T-cells in second

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:27.420
line of therapy. And so that tells us that it may not be important exactly when you give the CAR-T-cells,

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:31.640
at some point, and therefore you have to pick the time in patient's journey when the risk is most

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:36.920
justified. And then finally, I won't rehash what we already heard from Scott just earlier.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:42.160
The obvious, the elephant in the room here when thinking about CARs in first-line therapy are the

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:46.200
T-cell engagers. And if we think about CARs as a bit more complex, maybe a bit less predictable

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:51.120
risk profile, when you have results like this, where you have super high response rates,

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:56.860
number of denegativity rates, this is JSTIC-5, which Scott mentioned, even after three cycles

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:02.740
100% were MRD-negative after six cycles, 100% were MRD-negative at 10 to the minus six. And so

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:08.500
if we think MRD-negativity is long-term prognostic, it's hard to see how you do better than this. And

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:12.940
so you have to say, okay, if we're going to use CAR-T-cells instead, are they safer, or are they

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:18.140
in some other way more preferable? And so I think the appeal of CAR-T-cells would be that it is

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:24.220
one and done in this setting, whereas the bispecifics would entail some longer-term

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:28.240
exposure and risk. The consolidation approach with CAR-T-cells does seem

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:33.260
safer, but doesn't eliminate all the toxicity. But again, the tolerance for even rare toxicities,

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:37.020
they're serious and long-lasting, will be low considering the exceptional safety of

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:43.120
the alternatives. But I wonder, as we think about TCE-based therapies with fixed duration and

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:47.520
shorter regimens, could we get a lot of the benefit that we think of coming from CAR-T-cells and being

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:53.260
one and done, but in the form of a more accessible and more predictable therapy? That's all. Thank you very much.
